SIMPLE: hopper
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hopper
<hw>Hop"per</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See 1st
<er>Hop</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who, or that which,
hops.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A chute, box, or receptacle, usually funnel-shaped
with an opening at the lower part, for delivering or feeding any
material, as to a machine; <as>as, the wooden box with its trough
through which grain passes into a mill by joining or shaking, or a
funnel through which fuel passes into a furnace, or coal, etc.</as>,
into a car.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>See <er>Grasshopper</er>,
2.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>A game. See
<er>Hopscotch</er>.</def> <rj><au>Johnson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>See
<er>Grasshopper</er>, and <cref>Frog hopper</cref>, <cref>Grape
hopper</cref>, <cref>Leaf hopper</cref>, <cref>Tree hopper</cref>, under
<er>Frog</er>, <er>Grape</er>, <er>Leaf</er>, and <er>Tree</er>.</def>
<sd>(b)</sd> <def>The larva of a cheese fly.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>A vessel for carrying waste,
garbage, etc., out to sea, so constructed as to discharge its load by a
mechanical contrivance; -- called also <altname>dumping
scow</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Bell and hopper</b></col> <fld>(Metal.)</fld>, <cd>the
apparatus at the top of a blast furnace, through which the charge is
introduced, while the gases are retained.</cd> -- <col><b>Hopper
boy</b></col>, <cd>a rake in a mill, moving in a circle to spread meal
for drying, and to draw it over an opening in the floor, through which
it falls.</cd> -- <col><b>Hopper closet</b></col>, <cd>a water-closet,
without a movable pan, in which the receptacle is a funnel standing on a
draintrap.</cd> -- <col><b>Hopper cock</b></col>, <cd>a faucet or valve
for flushing the hopper of a water-closet.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hopperdozer</ent>⟦br⟧
